%page

Okay, a Little Exaggerated


	there are some tried and trusted tools

	and tools always have a role to play




%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%
%page

But, There's a Problem

	tools became a quick answer to all questions
		"how do I do $task?"

	users must trust trainers technical prowess, choices

	users don't update with new vulnerabilities

	users don't hear when the tools are deprecated

%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%
%page

The "Information Flow"

%size 4
someone picks a tool

trainers are convinced to teach the tool

users use the tool

tool is junk or vulnerabilities proliferate, or is deprecated

someone else picks another tool as the alternative

some trainers start preaching the alternative, but unclear why

some users continue to use the old tool, others adopt new tool

%font "italic", center
but ultimately the user is lost to any reasoning


%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%
%page

Whatever Happened to TrueCrypt?


	was in the "Holy Trinity" with Tor, PGP

	died an ugly sudden death

	how long did it take for the word to spread?

	did users migrate to a new tool? which?

	who is still training or using TrueCrypt?


%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%
%page

Let's be Honest Here

	a lot of tools are just utter crap

	poorly written, unaudited, not modular, not interoperable

	rely on regularly broken pieces, can you say O-p-e-n-S-S-L?

	complexity: just by using software thousands of lines of code
		which most likely you won't or can't audit

%center, font "italic"
so let's drop the "it's better than nothing" attitude
"more somethings" can often mean worse


