%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%
%page

So What Should Trainers Do?


	training isn't as easy as "hey just click this icon..."
		". . . instead of that other one"

	stop assuming the users should trust your technical knowledge
		vast majority of technical people don't really understand privacy tools

	don't look for short-cuts
		yes, tools are easy, but ultimately can be harmful

	teach methods, not tools
		let's explore that

%center, font "italic"
digital tools can be part of the answer, not the full solution unto themselves


%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%
%page

Fundamentals of Computing Services


	It's not about software or hardware, but rather about:

What problem are you trying to solve?

	Users should minimize trusting tools unless they can audit them
		or people they trust audit them

	you can't just train a user to write a random-number generator
		you can teach them they can't write one though

%font "italic"
assuming they really need the tools in the first place
if the users don't start employing the tools, trainings are considered failures
regardless of how ineffective or even dangerous those tools are


%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%
%page

Other Ideas


	"the more you carry in your head the less you carry on your back"

	remembering strong passwords: key to so many applications/systems
		cracking authentication is often default gateway for adversaries
		and stop trusting other peoples' password managers

	what do you want to do?

	what are the possible solutions?
		how would they solve it now?
		are there analog solutions?
		are there appropriate digital solutions?

	and the many caveats with digital solutions
		one-to-one comms now trust transit, end-points, tool developers
		keep it current and updated
		can I get an audit?

%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%
%page

Arm the Users: Threat-Modeling


	everyone is already doing it, help them with a lexicon

	Who are the adversaries and their resources?

	What are the stakes of being compromised?

	How much cost/effort/changes is the user willing to endure?

	How far will the adversaries go to compromise the user data/identity?



%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%
%page

Then Again, "What do you want?"


	specify what exactly the user wants/needs to do, in non-technical terms

	"tools" can work in creating solutions, but should not be the starting point
		coffee shop meeting might trump Signal

	non-digital tools should be considered

	going "multi-modal" mixing up digital and analog tools



%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%
%page

An Example: Email Encryption


	You want to teach or learn about encrypting email

	Either way, it's a good thing(TM)

	But users aren't taught about private/public keys
		and that public keys are like door locks
		and private keys are like physical keys

	And then users decide to or are instructed to put their private keys on their phone

%font "italic"
"but hey, at least I'm encrypting my email"


%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%
%page

Is Technology Always the Answer?


	Of course no, but it becomes self-fulfilling when you have trainers teaching tools

	starting with tools as opposed to starting with what problem are you trying to solve

	tools usually means dismissing other mediums and opportuntities
		face-to-face meetings
		intermodal-communcations (snail mail, voice, etc. ups the required sophistication of an adversary)
		reliance on pre-existing trust networks that are likely more robust than a tool




%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%
%page

Activists Usually Understand More


	long history of dissidents circumventing, hiding activities
		surveillance mitigation
		19th century Russian nihilists

	they are already doing something

	what is new is digitalization, the internet
		the telephone was equally "disruptive" is tranforming activism

